ce:section.ce:para:
After the preparation of GO, the characterization of GO is done using FESEM (Field Emission Scanning Electron Microscopy) along with EDS (Energy-dispersive X-ray spectroscopy) (Fig. 1
                     (a–d)). Fig. 1(a) shows a low-magnification scanning electron microscope (SEM) image, taken at 100x. The particles exhibit dispersion, indicating a heterogeneous mixture of varying flake sizes. Additionally, there is a notable presence of visible texture, implying a layered structure that is characteristic of GO. Fig. 1(b) and (c) represent a higher magnification SEM image, offering a closer look at the GO flakes. The sheet-like structure is evident here with some visible wrinkles and overlapping areas. These features are characteristic of GO, where the oxidation process introduces functional groups into the structure, disrupting the graphitic planes. The EDS analysis (Fig. 1(d)) shows some agglomerated forms in GO with significant C% and O%. To synthesize the GQD, oxidation of 3 g of GO is done using nitric acid (HNO3) and Sulphuric acid (H2SO4) by ultrasonication. The synthesized solution is then allowed to cool at room temperature and then 1200 ml of deionized (DI) water is added. To un-exfoliate the material, it is centrifuged at 3000 rpm. To remove the acidic group from the solution, it is first dialyzed using a dialysis bag and then mixed with ammonia solution (110 ml) and de-ionized water (80 ml). The formed solution was sonicated for 2 hrs. at a temperature of 90 °C followed by centrifuge at 1500 rpm. The formed suspension is dried using a rotary evaporator at 70 °C to obtain amine-treated graphene quantum dot powder. This powder form of quantum dots is further ultrasonicated in the PAG oil (base fluid) for 2 hrs. The nanosuspension is synthesized in three concentrations, that is 100 ppm, 200 ppm and 500 ppm. The synthesis of this solution is characterized using HRTEM (High-Resolution Transmission Electron Microscopy) (Fig. 2
                     ). The HRTEM image shows an even dispersion of amine-functionalized graphene quantum dots, suggesting a successful synthesis with precise control over the size distribution. The presence of crystallinity in the quantum dots demonstrates their structural integrity and confirms that the amine treatment did not have any negative impact on the crystalline structure of the graphene. This is crucial for preserving the electrical and optical properties of the GQDs. The stability of each solution is observed using an ultraviolet-spectrophotometer.
